name: Random.Set

values.name: notInSet
values.comment: Filter a generator of all values not in a given set.
values.type: Set.Set comparable -> Random.Generator comparable -> Random.Generator comparable

values.name: sample
values.comment:
Select a value from a set uniformly at random, or `Nothing` for an empty set.
Analogous to `Random.Extra.sample` but with sets.

values.name: set
values.comment:
Generate a set of at most the given size from a generator.

The size of a generated set is limited both by the integer provided and the
number of unique values the generator can produce. It is very likely, but not
guaranteed, that generated sets will be as big as the smaller of these two limits.

name: Random.Extra

values.name: andMap
values.comment:
Map over any number of generators.

    randomPerson : Generator Person
    randomPerson =
      map person genFirstName
        |> andMap genLastName
        |> andMap genBirthday
        |> andMap genPhoneNumber
        |> andMap genAddress
        |> andMap genEmail
values.type: Random.Generator a -> Random.Generator (a -> b) -> Random.Generator b

values.name: choice
values.comment:
Choose between two values with equal probability.

    type Flip = Heads | Tails

    coinFlip : Generator Flip
    coinFlip =
      choice Heads Tails

Note that this function takes values, not generators. That's because it's meant
to be a lightweight helper for a specific use. If you need to choose between two
generators, use `choices [gen1, gen2]`.

values.name: choices
values.comment:
Create a generator that chooses a generator from a list of generators
with equal probability.

**Warning:** Do not pass an empty list or your program will crash! In practice
this is usually not a problem since you pass a list literal.

values.name: combine
values.comment: Turn a list of generators into a generator of lists.

values.name: constant
values.comment:
Create a generator that always produces the value provided. This is useful
when creating complicated chained generators and you need to handle a simple
case. It's also useful for the base case of recursive generators.

values.name: filter
values.comment:
Filter a generator so that all generated values satisfy the given predicate.

    evens : Generator Int
    evens =
      filter (\i -> i % 2 == 0) (int minInt maxInt)

**Warning:** If the predicate is unsatisfiable, the generator will not
terminate, your application will crash with a stack overflow, and you will be
sad. You should also avoid predicates that are merely very difficult to satisfy.

    badCrashingGenerator =
      filter (\_ -> False) anotherGenerator

    likelyCrashingGenerator =
      filter (\i -> i % 2000 == 0) (int minInt maxInt)

values.name: frequency
values.comment:
Create a generator that chooses a generator from a list of generators
based on the provided weight. The likelihood of a given generator being
chosen is its weight divided by the total weight (which doesn't have to equal 1).

**Warning:** Do not pass an empty list or your program will crash! In practice
this is usually not a problem since you pass a list literal.
values.type: List ( Float, Random.Generator a ) -> Random.Generator a

values.name: map6
values.comment: Map a function of six arguments over six generators.
values.type: (a -> b -> c -> d -> e -> f -> g) -> Random.Generator a -> Random.Generator b -> Random.Generator c -> Random.Generator d -> Random.Generator e -> Random.Generator f -> Random.Generator g

values.name: maybe
values.comment:
Produce `Just` a value on `True`, and `Nothing` on `False`.

You can use `bool` or `oneIn n` for the first argument.
values.type: Random.Generator Bool -> Random.Generator a -> Random.Generator (Maybe.Maybe a)

values.name: oneIn
values.comment:
Produce `True` one-in-n times on average.

Do not pass a value less then one to this function.

    flippedHeads = oneIn 2
    rolled6 = oneIn 6

values.name: rangeLengthList
values.comment:
Generate a random list of random length given a minimum length and
a maximum length.
values.type: Int -> Int -> Random.Generator a -> Random.Generator (List a)

values.name: result
values.comment:
Produce an `Ok` a value on `True`, and an `Err` value on `False`.

You can use `bool` or `oneIn n` for the first argument.
values.type: Random.Generator Bool -> Random.Generator err -> Random.Generator val -> Random.Generator (Result.Result err val)

values.name: sample
values.comment:
Given a list, choose an element uniformly at random. `Nothing` is only
produced if the list is empty.

    type Direction = North | South | East | West

    direction : Generator Direction
    direction =
      sample [North, South, East, West]
        |> map (Maybe.withDefault North)
